Part 1: Choosing the Right Chart Type (20 minutes)

The Cardinal Rule

Your chart type should match the question youâre answering.

Not the data you have. Not the chart you think looks pretty. The question.

The Three Core Questions

Every business question falls into one of three categories:

1. Comparison - âWhich is bigger/better?â

Examples: - Which region has highest sales? - Which product is most profitable? - How do channels compare?

Best chart: Bar chart (horizontal or vertical)

Why it works: Humans are excellent at comparing bar lengths. We can instantly see âthis is bigger than that.â

Choose vertical bars when: - Few categories (2-7) - Category names are short

Choose horizontal bars when: - Many categories (8+) - Long category names (e.g., âBeauty & Personal Careâ) - Easier to read left-to-right

2. Trend Over Time - âHow is this changing?â

Examples: - Are sales growing or declining? - Whatâs the seasonal pattern? - Is performance improving?

Best chart: Line chart

Why it works: Lines naturally show direction (up, down, flat). Our eyes follow the path and see the story.

Line chart rules: - X-axis = Time (always!) - Y-axis = The metric (sales, profit, etc.) - Max 4-5 lines on one chart (more = spaghetti)

3. Composition - âWhatâs the breakdown?â

Examples: - What % of sales comes from each category? - How is the total divided? - Whatâs the market share?

Best chart: - Pie chart (use sparingly! Only 2-3 slices) - Stacked bar (better for 4+ categories) - Horizontal bar (often clearest option)

Why pie charts fail: - Hard to compare similar-sized slices - Human eyes are bad at comparing angles - Become unreadable with 6+ slices

When to use pie charts: - 2-3 categories maximum - Showing simple part-of-whole - Exact percentages donât matter much

Better alternative: Horizontal bar chart sorted by size. Easier to read, easier to compare.

When NOT to Use Certain Charts

Never use: - â 3D charts (distort perception, look dated) - â Pie charts with 7+ slices (unreadable) - â Multiple pie charts side-by-side (use grouped bars instead) - â Radar/spider charts (almost always confusing) - â Dual-axis charts with vastly different scales (misleading)

Part 2: Creating Clear Visualizations (25 minutes)

The Three Elements of a Good Chart

Every effective chart has three components:

1. A Clear Title (States the Insight!)

â Bad: âRegional Salesâ
â Good: âNorth Region Leads with 32% of Total Salesâ

The title should tell the story, not just label the topic.

Think of it as a headline: Whatâs the main finding?

2. Proper Labels

Must have: - Y-axis label (whatâs being measured) - Units (â¹, %, thousands, millions) - Data labels (if few data points < 10) - Legend (if multiple data series)

Example:

Y-axis: "Revenue (â¹ Millions)"
Not just: "Revenue"
Not just: "Millions"

3. Appropriate Scale

Rules: - Y-axis should usually start at zero for bar charts - Avoid broken axes unless clearly labeled - Use consistent scales when comparing charts - Donât exaggerate differences by manipulating scale

Example of misleading scale:

â Bad: Y-axis from â¹4.8M to â¹5.2M
   Makes 5% difference look like 500% difference

â Good: Y-axis from â¹0 to â¹6M
   Shows true proportional difference

Chart Anatomy Checklist

Before showing your chart to anyone, verify:

    • Never rely on color alone to convey information
    • Always label your data points with values
    • This helps everyone, especially those with color vision deficiency
    • NEVER use red-green combinations (8% of men have red-green color blindness)
    • Use high contrast combinations (blue-orange, blue-yellow)
    • Test in grayscale: Can you still tell categories apart?
    • Consider patterns/textures in addition to colors
    • Remove gridlines if not needed
    • Remove chart border
    • Simplify where possible

Step 4: Final Polish

Part 3: Building Insight Narratives (20 minutes)

The Insight Formula

A complete insight has three parts:

CHART + MESSAGE + RECOMMENDATION = INSIGHT

Chart alone: Just data
Chart + Message: Information
Chart + Message + Recommendation: Actionable insight

The Anatomy of a Strong Insight

â Weak Example: > âThis chart shows sales by region. North has the highest sales.â

(This just describes the chart. So what?)

â Strong Example: > âNorth region generates â¹4.2M (32% of total revenue), outperforming all other regions. However, South region is growing fastest (18% quarter-over-quarter) and may overtake North by year-end.
> > Recommendation: Increase inventory allocation to South to capitalize on growth momentum, while investigating why East and Central lag behind.â

See the difference? - States the pattern clearly (North leads) - Adds context (but South is growing faster) - Connects to business implications (may overtake by year-end) - Suggests concrete action (inventory allocation, investigation)

The âSo What?â Test

For every chart you create, ask three questions:

1. What does the data show? (The pattern)

Example: âBeverages revenue spiked in Q2 and Q3 of both years.â

2. Why does it matter? (The implication)

Example: âThis indicates strong seasonalityâsummer drives beverage sales.â

3. What should we do? (The recommendation)

Example: âPlan inventory and marketing budgets to peak in Q2-Q3. Explore ways to boost off-season sales with promotions or new products.â

If you canât answer all three, your chart isnât ready to present.

Writing Insight Narratives: Templates

Template 1: Highlight + Context + Action

â[Metric] shows [pattern]. This is significant because [reason]. We should [action].â

Example: > âOnline channel generates 45% of total revenue with an average transaction value of â¹68,000âsignificantly higher than Retail (â¹42,000). Template 2: Problem + Evidence + Solution

âWeâre facing [problem]. As the data shows, [evidence from chart]. To address this, I recommend [solution].â

Example: > âWeâre facing declining market share in the West region. As the data shows, West region revenue dropped 22% quarter-over-quarter while competitors grew 15% in the same market. To address this, I recommend: (1) competitive pricing audit within 1 week, (2) customer exit interviews to understand churn, (3) aggressive promotional campaign for Q4.â

Template 3: Opportunity + Proof + Next Steps

âThereâs an opportunity to [opportunity]. The data reveals [proof]. Next steps: [specific actions].â

Example: > âThereâs an opportunity to increase B2B penetration. The data reveals B2B customers have 3x higher average transaction value (â¹95K vs â¹32K) but represent only 15% of our customer base. Common Visualization Mistakes & Fixes

Mistake 1: Wrong Chart Type

â Problem: Using a pie chart with 8 slices - Hard to compare slice sizes - Labels overlap - Unreadable

â Fix: Use horizontal bar chart, sorted by size

â Problem: Using a line chart for categories - Lines imply continuity/trend - Categories like âProductsâ arenât sequential

â Fix: Use bar chart for categorical comparisons

Mistake 2: Misleading Scales

â Problem: Starting Y-axis at non-zero to exaggerate differences - Makes small differences look huge - Misleading to viewers

â Fix: - Start at zero for bar charts - If using non-zero start, clearly label it: âScale begins at â¹4Mâ

â Problem: Using inconsistent scales across charts - Canât compare charts side-by-side - Leads to wrong conclusions

â Fix: Use same scale for all comparison charts

Mistake 3: Too Much Information

â Problem: Showing 15 data series on one line chart - âSpaghetti chartâ - Impossible to read - No clear message

â Fix: - Show top 3-5 series - Group others as âOtherâ - Or create multiple charts

â Problem: Including every column from your dataset - Overwhelming - No clear focus

â Fix: Choose 1-2 metrics that answer your specific question

Mistake 4: Poor Visual Hierarchy

â Problem: All text same size, all bars same color - Nothing stands out - Eye doesnât know where to look

â Fix: - Highlight key data with color - Make title larger/bold - Use contrast strategically

Mistake 5: No Context

â Problem: Chart titled âSalesâ - Sales of what? When? Compared to what?

â Fix: âQ2 2024 Sales Grew 15% vs Q1, Driven by Beveragesâ - What happened - When - Why it matters

Excel Chart Tips & Tricks

Quick Chart Creation

Fastest way to create a chart: 1. Select your data 2. Press Alt + F1 â Creates default chart instantly 3. Or F11 â Creates chart in new sheet

Chart Formatting Shortcuts

Essential shortcuts: - Ctrl + 1 â Opens Format pane (works on any selected chart element) - Double-click any chart element â Opens formatting options - F4 â Repeat last action (great for formatting multiple elements)

Professional Color Palettes

CRITICAL: Color Blindness Affects 8-10% of Men and 0.5% of Women

Approximately 1 in 12 men and 1 in 200 women have some form of color vision deficiency. The most common is red-green color blindness.

Golden Rules for Accessible Colors:

  1. NEVER use red-green combinations
    • â Red for negative, green for positive (many people canât distinguish!)
    • â Blue for negative, orange for positive
    • â Or use blue + yellow, or blue + brown
  2. Use high contrast
    • Dark vs light, not similar shades
    • Test: View your chart in grayscaleâcan you still tell categories apart?
  3. Always label data points
    • Never rely on color alone
    • Add text labels showing actual values
    • This helps everyone, not just colorblind viewers
  4. Consider patterns in addition to colors
    • Striped bars vs solid bars
    • Dotted lines vs solid lines
    • Different marker shapes (circles, squares, triangles)

Recommended Color Palettes:

Safe Palette 1 (Blue-Orange): - Primary: #2E5090 (dark blue) - Secondary: #E67E22 (orange) - Neutral: #7F8C8D (gray) - Highlight: #F39C12 (yellow-orange)

Safe Palette 2 (Blue-Brown): - Primary: #3498DB (bright blue) - Secondary: #8B4513 (brown) - Neutral: #95A5A6 (light gray) - Highlight: #F1C40F (yellow)

Safe Palette 3 (Purple-Yellow): - Primary: #9B59B6 (purple) - Secondary: #F1C40F (yellow) - Neutral: #34495E (dark gray) - Highlight: #E67E22 (orange)

Colors to AVOID Together: - â Red + Green (most common color blindness) - â Blue + Purple (hard to distinguish for some) - â Green + Brown (can look similar) - â Light colors on light backgrounds

Best Practice Workflow: 1. Create your chart 2. Add data labels to all bars/points 3. Choose accessible color palette 4. Test in grayscale: Insert â Screenshot â Paste â Format Picture â Color â Grayscale 5. Can you still tell categories apart? If yes, youâre good! 6. If no, adjust colors or add patterns

Advanced Chart Tricks

1. Remove Chart Junk

Delete chart border: - Select chart area â Format â Shape Outline â No Outline

Simplify gridlines: - Make them light gray (#E0E0E0) - Or remove minor gridlines entirely

2. Add Data Labels Selectively

Donât label every point if you have 20+ data points.

Instead: - Label only min, max, or key values - Use callout boxes for important points - Add annotations with text boxes

3. Customize Axis Scales

Right-click axis â Format Axis - Set min/max bounds to focus on relevant range - Adjust intervals for cleaner appearance - Change to logarithmic scale if needed

4. Create Dynamic Titles

Make your chart title update automatically: 1. Click chart title 2. In formula bar, type = then click a cell 3. Title now updates when that cell changes

Example: Link title to a cell that says âQ2 2024 Performanceâ
